Developing a simple program to demonstrate file system encryption can be a great way to solidify your understanding of the coding practices involved. Here's a step-by-step guide to help you create a basic prototype:

**Project Overview:**

For this project, we'll create a simple program that encrypts and decrypts files using the AES encryption algorithm. We'll use the OpenSSL library to perform the encryption and decryption.

**Project Requirements:**

* Create a program that takes a file path as input and encrypts the file using AES encryption.
* Create a program that takes an encrypted file path as input and decrypts the file using AES decryption.
* Use the OpenSSL library to perform the encryption and decryption.
* Use a secure random number generator to generate a key for encryption and decryption.

**Project Structure:**

Create a new project with the following structure:
```bash
project/
main.c
aes_encrypt.c
aes_decrypt.c
Makefile
```
**main.c:**

This file will contain the main function that takes a file path as input and calls the encryption or decryption function based on the user's choice.
```c
#include <stdio.h>
#include <stdlib.h>
#include <string.h>
#include <openssl/aes.h>
#include <openssl/rand.h>

int main(int argc, char *argv[]) {
    if (argc != 3) {
        printf("Usage: %s <file_path> <encrypt/decrypt>\n", argv[0]);
        return 1;
    }

    char *file_path = argv[1];
    char *mode = argv[2];

    if (strcmp(mode, "encrypt") == 0) {
        aes_encrypt(file_path);
    } else if (strcmp(mode, "decrypt") == 0) {
        aes_decrypt(file_path);
    } else {
        printf("Invalid mode. Please use 'encrypt' or 'decrypt'.\n");
        return 1;
    }

    return 0;
}
```
**aes_encrypt.c:**

This file will contain the function that encrypts a file using AES encryption.
```c
#include <stdio.h>
#include <stdlib.h>
#include <string.h>
#include <openssl/aes.h>
#include <openssl/rand.h>

void aes_encrypt(char *file_path) {
    // Generate a key
    unsigned char key[32];
    RAND_bytes(key, 32);

    // Open the file for reading
    FILE *file = fopen(file_path, "rb");
    if (file == NULL) {
        printf("Error opening file: %s\n", file_path);
        return;
    }

    // Read the file contents
    fseek(file, 0, SEEK_END);
    long file_size = ftell(file);
    rewind(file);
    unsigned char *data = malloc(file_size);
    fread(data, 1, file_size, file);

    // Encrypt the data
    AES_KEY aes_key;
    AES_set_encrypt_key(key, 256, &aes_key);
    unsigned char *encrypted_data = malloc(file_size);
    AES_encrypt(data, encrypted_data, &aes_key);

    // Write the encrypted data to a new file
    char *encrypted_file_path = malloc(strlen(file_path) + 5);
    strcpy(encrypted_file_path, file_path);
    strcat(encrypted_file_path, ".enc");
    FILE *encrypted_file = fopen(encrypted_file_path, "wb");
    if (encrypted_file == NULL) {
        printf("Error opening encrypted file: %s\n", encrypted_file_path);
        return;
    }
    fwrite(encrypted_data, 1, file_size, encrypted_file);
    fclose(encrypted_file);

    // Free resources
    free(data);
    free(encrypted_data);
    free(encrypted_file_path);
    fclose(file);
}
```
**aes_decrypt.c:**

This file will contain the function that decrypts a file using AES decryption.
```c
#include <stdio.h>
#include <stdlib.h>
#include <string.h>
#include <openssl/aes.h>
#include <openssl/rand.h>

void aes_decrypt(char *file_path) {
    // Generate a key
    unsigned char key[32];
    RAND_bytes(key, 32);

    // Open the encrypted file for reading
    FILE *file = fopen(file_path, "rb");
    if (file == NULL) {
        printf("Error opening file: %s\n", file_path);
        return;
    }

    // Read the encrypted file contents
    fseek(file, 0, SEEK_END);
    long file_size = ftell(file);
    rewind(file);
    unsigned char *encrypted_data = malloc(file_size);
    fread(encrypted_data, 1, file_size, file);

    // Decrypt the data
    AES_KEY aes_key;
    AES_set_decrypt_key(key, 256, &aes_key);
    unsigned char *decrypted_data = malloc(file_size);
    AES_decrypt(encrypted_data, decrypted_data, &aes_key);

    // Write the decrypted data to a new file
    char *decrypted_file_path = malloc(strlen(file_path) + 5);
    strcpy(decrypted_file_path, file_path);
    strcat(decrypted_file_path, ".dec");
    FILE *decrypted_file = fopen(decrypted_file_path, "wb");
    if (decrypted_file == NULL) {
        printf("Error opening decrypted file: %s\n", decrypted_file_path);
        return;
    }
    fwrite(decrypted_data, 1, file_size, decrypted_file);
    fclose(decrypted_file);

    // Free resources
    free(encrypted_data);
    free(decrypted_data);
    free(decrypted_file_path);
    fclose(file);
}
```
**Makefile:**

This file will contain the build instructions for the program.
```makefile
CC = gcc
CFLAGS = -Wall -Wextra -pedantic -std=c11
LDFLAGS = -lcrypto

main: main.o aes_encrypt.o aes_decrypt.o
    $(CC) $(CFLAGS) $(LDFLAGS) -o main main.o aes_encrypt.o aes_decrypt.o

main.o: main.c
    $(CC) $(CFLAGS) -c main.c

aes_encrypt.o: aes_encrypt.c
    $(CC) $(CFLAGS) -c aes_encrypt.c

aes_decrypt.o: aes_decrypt.c
    $(CC) $(CFLAGS) -c aes_decrypt.c

clean:
    rm -f main.o aes_encrypt.o aes_decrypt.o main
```
**Build and Run:**

To build the program, run the following command:
```bash
make
```
To run the program, use the following command:
```bash
./main <file_path> <encrypt/decrypt>
```
Replace `<file_path>` with the path to the file you want to encrypt or decrypt, and `<encrypt/decrypt>` with either `encrypt` or `decrypt`.

Note that this is a basic prototype and you should not use it for production purposes. You should also be aware that this program uses a secure random number generator to generate a key, but it does not store the key securely. In a real-world application, you would need to store the key securely and use a secure key management system.

I hope this helps you create a basic prototype for file system encryption! If you have any further questions or need more information, feel free to ask.

